Performance Budget Contract


The dashboard currently has no declared performance boundaries. If Claude Code adds a heavy charting library, introduces a large client-side data transformation, or nests API calls sequentially where they could be parallel, nothing flags it. The middleware proxy returns JSON 502 on backend failure, but there's no contract that says "this page should load in under X seconds" or "this API call should resolve in under Y milliseconds." A performance budget manifest would declare the acceptable thresholds per page and per API route — initial page load time, largest contentful paint, total bundle size contribution per route, maximum sequential API calls per page load, and maximum acceptable payload size from any single endpoint. The path-scoped rule would trigger when Claude Code works on page components or API client code, injecting the budgets so it's aware of the constraints before adding dependencies or changing data-fetching patterns. The validator would check for obvious violations: new package imports that exceed a size threshold, sequential await chains that could be Promise.allSettled, API responses that exceed payload limits. This prevents the slow creep of performance degradation that's invisible on a developer's machine but painful on real networks — and it extends the Deal Integrity mission's Promise.allSettled discipline from a binary rule into a quantified performance architecture.
So the final five:

Surface 10 — Dependency Health (pre-task service topology awareness)
Surface 11 — Secret & Environment Variable Registry (cross-service config integrity)
Surface 12 — Error Taxonomy Contract (structured error routing beyond warn/error binary)
Surface 13 — Test Coverage Contract (declared coverage requirements per path)
Surface 14 — Performance Budget Contract (quantified performance thresholds per route)





